1. Data processing

We used QuPath (1) to perform unbiased detection and quantification of Iba1+ and CD-45+ cells in the ipsilateral hemisphere. The software generates _detections.tsv files containing the coordinates of individual cells and other measurements.

1.2 Batch processing of for image âdetectionsâ files

Here, we manipulate the _detections.tsv files containing the coordinates of individual cells to generate several .csv files with usable data.

Code 
process_initial_data <- function(basePath, Cells_Path, filename, resultsPath) {
  
  Cells_Raw <- read_tsv(paste0(basePath, "/", Cells_Path))
  
  # Convert to data frame
  Cells <- as.data.frame(Cells_Raw) 
  
  # Subset the date set to keep only relevant columns
  Cells <- subset(Cells, select = c(Image, Name, Class, `Centroid X Âµm`, `Centroid Y Âµm`))

  # Extract metadata information from image name
  Cells <- cbind(Cells, do.call(rbind , strsplit(Cells$Image , "[_\\.]"))[,1:2])
  colnames(Cells) <- c("Image", "ID", "Class", "X", "Y", "MouseID", "Condition")
  Cells <- subset(Cells, select = c(MouseID, Class, Condition, Image, ID, X, Y))
  
  # Write a .csv file 
  write.csv(Cells, paste0(resultsPath, "/", Cells_Path, filename))
}
basePath <- "QuPathProject"
resultsPath <- "ResultsTables/Cell_Coordinates"

process_folder <- function(folderPath, filename_suffix) {
  files <- list.files(folderPath, pattern = "_detections.tsv", full.names = FALSE)
  for (file in files) {
    process_initial_data(folderPath, file, filename_suffix, resultsPath)
  }
}

process_folder(paste0(basePath, "/CD45"), "_Coordinates.csv")
process_folder(paste0(basePath, "/Iba1"), "_Coordinates.csv")
process_folder(paste0(basePath, "/CD45High"), "_Coordinates.csv")

1.2 Create the point patterns

Using the the newly generated _Coordinates.csv files for Iba1 and CD-45, we create point patterns using the functions from the spatstat package (2).The point patterns are stored as a hyperframe object in PointPatterns/PPP_Ipsilateral_5x.RDS.

Code 
set.seed(88071)

coordinatesPath <- "ResultsTables/Cell_Coordinates"

# Results to generate
Result_Hyperframe <- NULL

# Functions

add_to_hyperframe <- function (...) {
    if (is.null(Result_Hyperframe)){
      Result_Hyperframe <<- hyperframe(...)
    } else {
      Result_Hyperframe <<- rbind(Result_Hyperframe, hyperframe(...))
    }
}

# Cretate a point pattern (PPP) object

create_point_pattern <- function(Raw) {
  # We define the limits of the window according to Neuron coordinates
  xlim <- range(Raw$X)
  ylim <- range(Raw$Y)

  # Create point pattern for neurons
  Cells_PPP <- with(Raw, ppp(x = Raw$X, y = Raw$Y, xrange = xlim, yrange = ylim))
  unitname(Cells_PPP)  <- list("mm", "mm", 3.911/4308)
  Cells_PPP <- spatstat.geom::rescale (Cells_PPP)
  
  ## We rescale the unit to obtain measurements in mm2
  return(Cells_PPP)
  
}

process_file <- function (basePath, path) {

  Iba1_Raw <- read.csv(file = paste0(basePath, '/', path, '_Iba1_detections.tsv_Coordinates.csv'), header = TRUE)
 # CD45_Raw <- read.csv(file = paste0(basePath, '/', path, #'_CD45_detections.tsv_Coordinates.csv'), header = TRUE)
  CD45High_Raw <- read.csv(file = paste0(basePath, '/', path, '_CD45High_detections.tsv_Coordinates.csv'), header = TRUE)

  
  Iba1_PPP <- create_point_pattern(Iba1_Raw)
  #CD45_PPP <- create_point_pattern(CD45_Raw)
  CD45High_PPP <- create_point_pattern(CD45High_Raw)

  fragments <- strsplit(path, "_")[[1]]
  len <- length(fragments)
  Mouse <- fragments[1]
  Condition <- fragments[2]
  
  add_to_hyperframe(CD45High = CD45High_PPP, Iba1 = Iba1_PPP, Mouse = Mouse, Condition=Condition, stringsAsFactors=TRUE) 
  
}

csv_files <- list.files(coordinatesPath, full.names = FALSE, recursive = FALSE)

brains <- c()

for (csv in csv_files) {
  fragments <- strsplit(csv, "_")[[1]]
  brain_name <- paste(fragments[1:2], collapse="_")
  brains <- append(brains, brain_name)
}

brains <- unique(brains)

for (brain in brains) {
  process_file(coordinatesPath, brain)
}

3. Fit a point process model

We fit a spatial model for replicated point patterns using the mppm function from spatstat to estimate differences between the spatial intensity in WT and DKK1 mice. The model takes the notation:

\(Î»(u) = \exp(Âµ + Î±_{Condition(u)})\)

Were the parameters Î± are the influence of each condition (WT or DKK).

Code 
# Fit model for CD45
CD45_fit1 <- mppm(CD45High ~ Condition, PPP_Iba1_CD45)

# We extract the confidence intervals
CD45_fit1_CI <- confint(CD45_fit1)

4. Plot density maps for Iba1 and CD45

In this section, we use the superimpose function to merge (superimpose) all the point patterns per group. Then, the unmark function is employed to allow the calculation of a density kernel (the density function is not available for marked point patterns. Next, we calculate the density kernel per group, using the density function and plot the images.

Code 
# Superimpose brains for Iba1
Iba1_Superimposed_WT <- superimpose(PPP_Iba1_CD45_WT$Iba1) 
Iba1_Superimposed_WT <- unmark(Iba1_Superimposed_WT)

Iba1_Superimposed_DKK1 <- superimpose(PPP_Iba1_CD45_Dkk1$Iba1) 
Iba1_Superimposed_DKK1 <- unmark(Iba1_Superimposed_DKK1)

# Plot superimposed brains
Iba1_Density_WT <- density(Iba1_Superimposed_WT, sigma = 0.05)
Iba1_Density_DKK1 <- density(Iba1_Superimposed_DKK1, sigma = 0.05)

Iba1_Super_Colmap <- colourmap(topo.colors(250), range = c(0, 12000))

plot(Iba1_Density_WT, col=Iba1_Super_Colmap)
plot(Iba1_Density_DKK1, col= Iba1_Super_Colmap)

5. Additional data analysis

5.1 Analysis of neurological score

We fit an ordinal logistic regression model using the âpolrâ function from the MASS package (3) to analyze the neurological score at 24 hours and 3 days following injury. We use âscoreâ as the outcome variable, and âTimeâ and âGroupâ as predictor variables.

Code 
# We load the data set
NeurologicalScore <- read.csv(file = 'NSS Dkk1-stroke.csv', header = TRUE)

# We specify the factor levels for Gropus
NeurologicalScore$Group <- factor(NeurologicalScore$Group, levels = c("DKK1/OFF", "WT/DOX", "DKK1/ON"))

# We convert the score to factor (ordered)
NeurologicalScore$Score <- as.factor(NeurologicalScore$Score)

# Fit the model
NeurologicalScore_Mdl1 <- polr(as.ordered(Score) ~ Time * Group, data = NeurologicalScore, Hess = TRUE)

# Print a summary of the model
summary(NeurologicalScore_Mdl1)

5.2 Analysis of horizontal bar test

We fit an ordinal logistic regression model to analize using the horizontal bar test at 24 hours and 3 days following injury. Please note that the scores (time on the rod) are represented as ratios to the baseline value. We preformed a quartile division of the score (â0-0.25â, â0.25-0.50â, â0.50-0.75â, â0.75-1â) as the outcome variable, and âTimeâ and âGroupâ as predictor variables.

Code 
# We load the data set
HorizontalBar <- read.csv(file = 'DataTables/HorizontalBar_V2.csv', header = TRUE)

# We specify the factor levels for Groups
HorizontalBar$Group <- factor(HorizontalBar$Group, levels = c("DKK1/OFF", "WT/DOX", "DKK1/ON"))

# Define the range boundaries
range <- c(0, 0.25, 0.50, 0.75, 1)
ordinal_labels <- c("0-0.25", "0.25-0.50", "0.50-0.75", "0.75-1")

convert_to_ordinal <- function(Score) {
  category <- cut(Score, range, labels = ordinal_labels, include.lowest = TRUE)
  return(as.character(category))
}

# Apply the conversion function to the Time column in the data set
HorizontalBar$Range <- convert_to_ordinal(HorizontalBar$Score)

# We convert the score to factor (ordered)
HorizontalBar$Range <- factor(HorizontalBar$Range, levels = c("0-0.25", "0.25-0.50", "0.50-0.75", "0.75-1"))

# Fit the model
HorizontalBar_Mdl1 <- polr(as.ordered(Range) ~ Time * Group, data = HorizontalBar, Hess = TRUE)

# Print a summary of the model
summary(HorizontalBar_Mdl1)

5.1.1 Plot the horizontal bar score (line plot)

Next, we use the predict function to generate predictions in the probability scale for each score based on the fitted model.

Code 
# Create a new data frame for predictions
newdata <- expand.grid(Time = unique(HorizontalBar$Time),
                       Group = levels(HorizontalBar$Group))


# Generate predictions
predictions <- predict(HorizontalBar_Mdl1, newdata = newdata, type = "probs")

# Rename columns of predictions to ensure they're unique
colnames(predictions) <- paste0("Range_", colnames(predictions))

# Add the predictions to the new data frame
newdata <- cbind(newdata, predictions)

# Convert to long format for plotting
predictions_long <- tidyr::pivot_longer(newdata, cols = starts_with("Range_"), 
                                        names_to = "Range", values_to = "Probability")

5.3. DKK1 and IgG correlation

We perform a correlation between DKK1 expression and IgG. First, we load the data set

Code 
DKK1_IgG <- read.csv(file = 'DataTables/DKK1_IgG.csv', header = TRUE)

5.3.1 Initial data visualization

Code 
ggplot(DKK1_IgG, aes(x = DKK1, y = IgG)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(
  method = "lm", 
  se     = TRUE,
  color  = "black") +
geom_smooth(

  geom_smooth(
  method  = "lm", 
  se      = TRUE, 
  formula = y ~ poly(x, 3), 
  color   = "darkgreen")

The graph shows DKK1 values who reached a threshold in the Elisa essay. For this reason, we are going to perform a regression excluding those values. Later, we use the model to make predictions for DKK1 values based on their IgG.

First, we exclude the DKK1 values reaching the threshold above 14000.

Code 
filtered_data <- DKK1_IgG %>%
  filter(DKK1 <= 14000)

We plot again the function

Code 
ggplot(filtered_data, aes(x = DKK1, y = IgG)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(
  method = "lm", 
  se     = TRUE,
  color  = "black") +
geom_smooth(
  method  = "lm", 
  se      = TRUE,

  color   = "darkred") +
  geom_smooth(
  method  = "lm", 
  se      = TRUE, 
  formula = y ~ poly(x, 3), 
  color   = "darkgreen")

Now, we see that the similarity with linearity is stronger. Therefore, we are going to postulate a liner model to fit the data.

Code 
DKK1_IgG_Model <- lm(DKK1 ~ IgG, data = filtered_data)
